INSERT INTO `songbirds` VALUES (1,'Western Scrub-Jay','Western-Scrub jay','corvids',2,'blue','white','greey','Null','Null',0,'blue','black','',0,'brown','common','common','common','common','m','Aphelocoma californica','scrub_jay.jpg','',1,'','','','','','0','0','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/26224125/DSCF4678.jpg','','Scrub jays live in low-growing oak scrub and scrubby flatwoods, which are found in sand ridges, ancient sandy ridges, old sand dunes, and sandy deposits in Florida. These habitats are dry and sandy, with interspersed sandy openings, and low-lying myrtle, Chapman\'s oak, and shrubs. Scrub jays are the only bird species endemic to Florida, meaning they are found nowhere else in the world.',' California scrub jay\'s range extends from the western coast of Canada, down to the Baja Peninsula in Mexico, and parts of Nevada. It\'s non-migratory, meaning it stays in the same territory year-round, though it may travel to find food if acorns become scarce.',0),(2,'American Crow','American Crow','corvids',2,'black','black','brown','Null','Null',1,'black','black','',1,'black','common','common','common','common','l','Corvus brachyrhynchos','american_crow.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/09173621/DSCF0229a-scaled.jpg',1,'females are slightly smaller than males ','The American Crow (Corvus brachyrhynchos) is a large, intelligent, all-black bird, including its legs and bill. It is a widespread species found throughout North America, thriving in a variety of habitats including forests, agricultural lands, and urban areas. American Crows are highly adaptable and omnivorous, feeding on a wide range of food items from insects and small animals to fruits and seeds, and even human food waste. \r\n','The American crow (Corvus brachyrhynchos) is a large bird with long legs, a thick neck, and a straight bill. It has glossy black feathers, a short tail, and broad, rounded wings. The American crow is 16–21 in long, with the tail making up about 40% of its body length. Its wingspan is 33–39 in, and its wing chord is 9.6–13 in <br>\r\n\r\n\r\nThe American crow is common in the lower 48 states and can be found in open areas near woods, human-modified landscapes, backyards, and cemeteries. It\'s known for its loud caw, and is often recognizable by its distinctive, glossy sheen. <br>\r\nAmerican crows are omnivorous ground foragers that eat small animals, grain, fruits, insects, and carrion. They\'re opportunistic eaters that will eat whatever is available, and often take advantage of human garbage. In the fall and winter, they eat more nuts, such as walnuts and acorns. <br>\r\n\r\nAmerican crows are also significant nest predators, preying on the eggs and nestlings of smaller songbirds. ','diverse, innovative,resilient,dedicated, dynamic, skillfull, collaborative, patriotic, professional, optimistic','32b637ca6f2fa60b34c972eb1686eda3','0','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/12222720/crow3.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/09173621/DSCF0229a-scaled.jpg','https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.jonswanservices.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2022%2F03%2F09173621%2FDSCF0229a-scaled.jpg','Crows live in many different habitats around the world, including woodlands, farms, cities, tidal flats, agricultural fields and orchards, riparian forests, and savannas. For example, American crows prefer open areas with trees nearby, such as agricultural land and grasslands. They also thrive in suburban neighborhoods and urban parks, as well as in coastal habitat','American crows (Corvus brachyrhynchos) are native to North America and can be found throughout central and eastern regions, from Newfoundland to Florida and Texas, and in northern Mexico. Their range includes the Pacific Ocean, the Atlantic Ocean, the French islands of Saint-Pierre and Miquelon, and most of the lower 48 states, excluding the southwestern deserts. They can also be found in forests, towns, and agricultural areas, such as open areas near woods, city parks, garbage dumps, campgrounds, lawns, athletic fields, cemeteries, and parking lots',0),(3,'Stellars Jay','Stellars Jay','corvids',2,'blue','black',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'black','blue','',0,'common','f','u','u','u','m','Cyanocitta stelleri','steller\'s_jay.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/29011931/DSCF2631.jpg',1,'Both Sexes look the same but females are slightly smaller than males.','The Steller\'s Jay (Cyanocitta stelleri) is a striking and intelligent bird native to western North America. Recognizable by its vibrant blue and black plumage and distinctive crest on its head, it is the largest of the North American jays. The Steller\'s Jay exhibits strong regional color variations, with coastal birds typically showing darker shades. These birds are known for their loud, harsh calls and remarkable adaptability. They are omnivores, feeding on a diet that includes insects, seeds, berries, and occasionally small animals. The Steller\'s Jay, named after the German naturalist Georg Wilhelm Steller, is a bold and curious bird, often seen visiting campsites and picnic areas in search of food.','Nature is a canvas upon which countless masterpieces are painted, each displaying its unique beauty and captivating observers with its intricate details. Among these works of art is the Steller\'s Jay, a bird that graces the forests of North America with its vibrant plumage and majestic presence. In this essay, we will explore the captivating beauty of the Steller\'s Jay, delving into its physical characteristics, behavior, and cultural significance.\r\n\r\nPhysical Characteristics:\r\n\r\nThe Steller\'s Jay (Cyanocitta stelleri) is a medium-sized songbird belonging to the Corvidae family. Its striking appearance makes it instantly recognizable. The bird boasts a deep blue plumage, which covers its head, back, wings, and tail. The feathers on its head form a distinctive crest, giving it an appearance of regality. Complementing its azure coat, the Steller\'s Jay features black markings on its face, throat, and upper body, creating a stunning contrast. Its eyes are a deep, piercing black, adding an air of mystery to its overall appearance.\r\n\r\nBehavior:\r\n\r\nBeyond its physical beauty, the Steller\'s Jay possesses a captivating personality and behavior that further enhances its allure. These birds are known for their intelligence, adaptability, and resourcefulness. They are highly social creatures, often found in pairs or small groups, engaging in complex vocalizations to communicate with one another. Their calls, a combination of harsh screeches and melodious whistles, echo through the forest, adding a symphony of sound to their visual splendor.\r\n\r\nThe Steller\'s Jay is also renowned for its remarkable mimicry skills. It can imitate the calls of other birds, as well as various natural sounds, displaying its versatility as a vocal artist. This mimicry not only aids in communication but also serves as a defense mechanism, confusing potential predators.\r\n\r\nCultural Significance:\r\n\r\nThe beauty of the Steller\'s Jay extends beyond its physical appearance and behavior. It holds cultural significance for many indigenous communities across North America. In Native American folklore, the Steller\'s Jay is often associated with transformation and adaptability. Its ability to thrive in diverse habitats and its resourcefulness in finding food and shelter are seen as lessons in resilience and survival.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, the vibrant blue color of the Steller\'s Jay has cultural and spiritual symbolism. Blue is often associated with wisdom, spirituality, and protection in various indigenous traditions. The presence of the Steller\'s Jay, with its resplendent blue plumage, is believed to bring good fortune and positive energy.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\n\r\nThe Steller\'s Jay is a true marvel of nature\'s artistry, captivating observers with its stunning appearance, enchanting vocalizations, and cultural significance. Its vibrant blue plumage, adorned with black markings and a regal crest, makes it a visual spectacle. Its intelligence, adaptability, and mimicry skills further enhance its allure, while its cultural symbolism adds a deeper layer of appreciation. The Steller\'s Jay serves as a reminder of the intricate beauty that exists in the natural world, urging us to cherish and protect these magnificent creations.','','c31d4030aaf170b87bcf3bff35b358f0','0','','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/29012028/DSCF2614.jpg','https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.jonswanservices.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2021%2F01%2F12222202%2Fstellers-scaled.jpg','\r\n\r\nSteller\'s jays (Cyanocitta stelleri) are native to western North America and live in coniferous and coniferous-deciduous forests, as well as arid pine-oak woodlands in Mexico and the southwestern U.S.. They are most commonly found in the mountains and along the northern coast, in forests of pine, spruce, and fir. Steller\'s jays also live in the Pacific coastal foothills, where they can be found at elevations of 3,000-10,000 feet.','\r\nSteller\'s jays (Cyanocitta stelleri) are found in the forested areas of western North and Central America, from southern Alaska to Nicaragua. They live in coniferous and mixed mountain forests, from the foothills of the Rocky Mountains to the Mexican highlands. Steller\'s jays are often permanent residents, but may move to lower elevations in the winter. They may also invade lowlands if food crops fail in the mountains',0),(4,'Barn Swallow','Barn Swallow','swallows ',3,'blue','orange','black','Null','Null',0,'blue','orange','',0,'brown','common','common','common','common','s','Hirundo rustica','barn_swallow.jpg','',1,'Female barn swallows are similar in appearance to males, but have shorter tail streamers, paler underparts, and less glossy upperparts and breast band. They also tend to be less vibrantly colored','A barn swallow is a small, agile bird known for its sleek body and long, forked tail. It has a striking appearance with a blue-black back, wings, and tail, contrasting beautifully with its reddish-orange throat and forehead. The underparts are a pale, creamy color. Barn swallows are renowned for their extraordinary flying skills, darting gracefully through the air to catch insects in flight. They are often associated with rural areas and farmlands, where they frequently build their cup-shaped mud nests on the beams and eaves of barns and other structures, hence their name. These birds are migratory, traveling great distances between their breeding grounds in the Northern Hemisphere and wintering areas in the Southern Hemisphere.','\r\nBarn swallows are sparrow-sized birds with broad shoulders that taper to long, pointed wings. They have a steel blue back, wings, and tail, and tawny underparts. The throat and forehead is rusty. Adults are brightly marked in deep blue, rusty, and cinnamon. Barn swallows grow to between 5.5 and 7 inches in length with a wingspan of 12.5 to 13.5 inches. When perched, it appears cone-shaped, with a slightly flattened head and no visible neck. The tail extends well beyond the wingtips and the long outer feathers give the tail a deep fork. Barn swallows are aerial foragers that eat insects and live in grasslands. They can be found across most of North America. Barn swallows can be seen feeding above meadows, fields, and farmyards; feeding over water; perched on wires near feeding areas and nesting sites; and picking up mud and grass from mud puddles for nesting materials. Barn swallows build mud nests under the eaves of barns and stables, on structures near playing fields, or under bridges. They may also use artificial nest cups or build a nest on a provided shelf. Barn swallows usually produce two broods per season.\r\nBarn swallows are the most abundant swallow species on the planet and are found in both hemispheres. They are a migratory species and winter in South America, Africa, and Asia.','small, elegant, long, pointed, forked, steely blue, rufous, tawny, dark orange, and agile.','','0','0','','','\r\nBarn swallows are very adaptable birds. They can nest anywhere where there are open areas for foraging, a water source, and a sheltered ledge for their nest. They seek out open habitats of all types, including farms, and are commonly found in barns or other outbuildings.','\r\nBarn owls typically use one nest site, 1–3 main roost sites, and other sites that may occasionally be occupied. Some sites are only used while the birds are nesting, while others are only used in winter. Home ranges overlap, and the extent to which this happens is related to the population density of barn owls, which is largely determined by the landscape.',0),(5,'Bushtit','Bushtit','chickadees_bushtits',4,'grey','brown','yellow','Null','Null',0,'grey','grey','',1,'NA','common','common','common','common','t','Psaltriparus minimus','male_bushtit.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/03012238/DSCF8629.jpg',0,'Female Bushtits have yellow eyes and males have black eyes.','Bushtits are small, gregarious birds belonging to the family Aegithalidae. Known for their energetic and social behavior, they are predominantly found across the western parts of North America. These tiny birds exhibit a soft, gray plumage, and although their coloration is generally muted, it offers them excellent camouflage in their natural habitats, which include woodlands, gardens, and shrublands.\n\nOne of the most distinctive features of bushtits is their long, pendulous nests, which are meticulously constructed from moss, spider silk, and other fine materials. These nests can house the entire flock during breeding season, providing warmth and protection for the eggs and chicks.\n\nBushtits are primarily insectivorous, feeding on a variety of insects and spiders. Their foraging behavior is quite fascinating to observe, as they move in large, noisy flocks, flitting from branch to branch in search of food. Despite their small size, bushtits play a significant role in controlling insect populations in their ecosystems.\n\nTheir vocalizations are typically soft and subtle, consisting of quiet chirps and buzzes that can be heard as they communicate within their flocks. The social structure of bushtit flocks is complex, with strong bonds formed between flock members, often seen huddling together for warmth and safety.\n\nBushtits are a delight for birdwatchers, offering insights into the intricate social behaviors and survival strategies of small passerines. Their presence is indicative of a healthy, insect-rich environment, underscoring the importance of conserving their natural habitats.','Bushtits are small, social birds with large heads, long tails, and short bills that are about the size of a kinglet, slightly smaller than a chickadee. They are brown and gray in color, with darker plumage in humid coastal areas. Bushtits have short necks, round bodies, and short, pointed bills. Males have dark eyes, while females have light-colored (or golden) eyes.','small, elegant, long, pointed, forked, steely blue, rufous, tawny, and dark orange. ','1a62c2477109a5de4bc7758591ee0e84','0','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/03012337/DSCF8741.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/03012407/DSCF9434.jpg','https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.jonswanservices.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2021%2F04%2F03012503%2Fbushtit.jpg','Open woods, scrubby areas, pine-oak woodlands, chaparral, suburbs, parks, dry scrublands, streamsides, low branches of open woodlands, edges, and neighborhood vegetation.','\r\n\r\nBushtits are found in western North America, from the southernmost part of western Canada to Guatemala, Mexico, and the western United States. They are mainly resident in the western United States and high parts of Mexico, and their range includes the Great Basin, the lowlands and foothills of California, southern Mexico, and Guatemala.',0),(6,'Black-Capped Chickadee','Black-Capped Chickadee','chickadees_bushtits',4,'grey','black','white','brown','Null',0,'black','white','',0,'brown','common','common','common','common','s','Poecile atricapillus','black_capped_chicadee.jpg',NULL,1,'','A chickadee is a small, charismatic bird known for its distinctive call that sounds like \"chick-a-dee-dee-dee,\" from which it gets its name. These birds are part of the tit family Paridae, primarily found in North America. They have round bodies, large heads, short necks, and long, narrow tails. Chickadees are easily recognizable by their black caps and bibs, white cheeks, gray backs, wings, and fluffy underparts. They are curious and friendly towards humans, often found flitting about in forests, suburban, and urban areas, feeding on seeds, insects, and suet. Chickadees are also known for their remarkable memory, able to recall thousands of hiding places where they store food for the winter.','Introduction:\r\nThe chickadee, a small passerine bird belonging to the Paridae family, is a remarkable creature that has captured the interest of scientists and bird enthusiasts alike. With its distinctive appearance, unique vocalizations, and intriguing behavioral patterns, the chickadee serves as an excellent subject for study. This essay explores the various aspects of the chickadee\'s life, focusing on its remarkable adaptations for survival and its complex social behavior.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','','','0','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/02225224/DSCF8507.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/27234246/DSCF6432.jpg','https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.jonswanservices.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F01%2F20192312%2FBrownCreeper.jpg','Black-capped chickadees are found in deciduous and mixed deciduous-evergreen forests, especially near forest edges. They are commonly found near willows and cottonwoods, and like to make their nests in the snags of alder and birch trees. Feeders and nest boxes can be used to attract chickadees to suburban backyards.','The black-capped chickadee (Parus atricapillus) is found from New England to the West Coast, and south to New Mexico in the West, and south to Georgia in the East. It also occurs in Alaska and Yukon, and throughout the southern half of Canada.',0),(7,'Brown Creeper','Brown Creeper','nuthatches_creepers',5,'brown','white','grey',NULL,NULL,0,'brown','white','',0,'brown','frequent','frequent ','frequent ','frequent ','t','Certhia Americana','brown_creeper.jpg',NULL,1,'','Brown Creepers, scientifically known as Certhia americana, are small, inconspicuous birds that inhabit woodland areas across North America. These birds are named for their distinctive brown mottled plumage that serves as excellent camouflage against tree bark, and their unique behavior of creeping upward in a spiral around tree trunks while searching for insects in the crevices of the bark. Brown Creepers are slender birds with long, stiff tail feathers that they use as support while navigating vertical surfaces. They have a slender, downcurved bill that is perfectly adapted for extracting insects and spiders from bark. Their song is a high, thin whistle, often going unnoticed by those not specifically listening for it. Despite their widespread presence, Brown Creepers can be challenging to spot due to their cryptic appearance and quiet nature, making them a delightful surprise for bird watchers who manage to spot these elusive creatures.','The Fascinating Brown Creepers: Masters of Camouflage and Adaptation\r\n\r\nIntroduction:\r\nThe natural world is full of marvels, each species with its unique set of adaptations and characteristics. Among these fascinating creatures is the brown creeper (Certhia americana), a small bird that has mastered the art of camouflage and adaptation. In this essay, we will explore the intriguing world of brown creepers, examining their physical attributes, habitat preferences, foraging techniques, and remarkable adaptations that make them truly exceptional birds.\r\n\r\nPhysical Attributes and Habitat Preferences:\r\nBrown creepers, as their name suggests, are predominantly brown in color, allowing them to blend seamlessly with the bark of trees they inhabit. They have a slender body, measuring around 12-13 centimeters in length, with a long, curved beak that aids in their feeding behavior. Their plumage is streaked with shades of brown, providing them with excellent camouflage against tree trunks. This remarkable adaptation helps them remain hidden from predators and potential prey.\r\n\r\nBrown creepers are primarily found in mature and old-growth forests across North America. They have a preference for coniferous and mixed forests, where they can find suitable trees for nesting and foraging. These habitats offer an abundance of insects, their primary source of food.\r\n\r\nForaging Techniques and Diet:\r\nThe feeding behavior of brown creepers is distinct and intriguing. Unlike most birds that search for food in the air or on the ground, brown creepers have evolved to forage vertically along tree trunks. They start at the bottom and work their way up, using their sharp beaks to pick insects and spiders from crevices in the bark. Their long, curved beak provides them with the necessary leverage to extract prey effectively.\r\n\r\nTheir diet primarily consists of insects, spiders, and other arthropods found on the trees. They are particularly fond of tree-dwelling insects, such as beetles and caterpillars. To further supplement their diet, brown creepers also consume small amounts of seeds and berries during the winter months when insects are scarce.\r\n\r\nRemarkable Adaptations:\r\nThe brown creeper\'s remarkable adaptations extend beyond their physical attributes and foraging techniques. One of the most notable adaptations is their ability to blend in with their surroundings. Their streaked plumage, combined with their ability to climb upwards along tree trunks, allows them to remain virtually invisible to predators and unsuspecting prey.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, brown creepers have an extraordinary ability to rotate their stiff tail feathers, using them as a prop while climbing. This adaptation provides them with stability and balance, enabling them to navigate effortlessly on vertical surfaces. Such adaptations not only aid in their foraging behavior but also protect them from potential predators lurking in the trees.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nThe brown creeper is an extraordinary bird, exemplifying the wonders of adaptation and camouflage in the natural world. Through their physical attributes, habitat preferences, foraging techniques, and remarkable adaptations, they have successfully carved out a niche in the forest ecosystems of North America. The ability to blend seamlessly with their surroundings and their unique foraging behavior make brown creepers a true wonder of nature. Studying and appreciating these fascinating birds not only expands our knowledge of avian diversity but also deepens our understanding of the intricate interconnections within ecosystems.','','7b26607dcfb9bb955d08556d1755234c','0','https://www.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/DSCF9735.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/20192312/BrownCreeper.jpg','https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.jonswanservices.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F01%2F20192312%2FBrownCreeper.jpg','','',0),(8,'Bewick’s Wren','Bewick’s Wren','wrens_kinglets',6,'brown','white ','Null','Null','Null',0,'brown','grey','',0,'brown','common','common','common','common','t','hryomanes bewickii nesophilus','bewick\'s_wren.jpg','',1,'','The Bewick\'s Wren (Thryomanes bewickii) is a small songbird native to North America, named after the British engraver Thomas Bewick. This bird is easily identified by its long, slender tail, which it often holds upright, and its distinctive white eyebrow stripe. The plumage of the Bewick\'s Wren is primarily brown, with lighter underparts and subtle barring on the wings and tail. \n\nBewick\'s Wrens are known for their loud and complex songs, which males use to defend territories and attract mates. They are adaptable birds, inhabiting a variety of environments including woodlands, thickets, and even urban areas, where they can be found foraging for insects and spiders in brush piles and undergrowth.\n\nDespite their adaptability, the populations of Bewick\'s Wrens have faced declines in certain areas, primarily due to habitat loss and competition with other species. Conservation efforts are focused on preserving their habitats and understanding the factors that influence their population dynamics.','','','5c4905d5155c11222dc4fc86684cedb0','','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/18144036/DSCF7679-1024x732.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/09122940/DSCF0658.jpg','https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.jonswanservices.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2022%2F02%2F18144036%2FDSCF7679-scaled.jpg','','',0),(9,'Ruby-Crowned Kinglet','Ruby-Crowned Kinglet','wrens_kinglets',6,'olive_green','grey','brown','','red',0,'olive_green','grey','',0,'brown','c','u','c','c','t','Regulus calendula','ruby_crowned_kinglet.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/03200826/rubycrowned-scaled.jpg',1,'The females do not have the red crown. ','The Ruby-crowned Kinglet is a small songbird that is found in North America. It is one of the smallest birds in North America, measuring only about 4 inches in length. The bird is named for the ruby-red crown patch on the head of the male, which is usually concealed. The female lacks the ruby crown and has a yellow patch on her head instead. Ruby-crowned Kinglets are known for their high-pitched, rapid songs and their active, restless behavior as they flit through trees and shrubs in search of insects and spiders to eat. They breed in the boreal forests of Canada and Alaska and migrate south to the United States and Mexico for the winter.',NULL,'Tiny,\r\nFast,\r\nRestless,\r\nAcrobatic,\r\nOlive-green,\r\nOlive-buff,\r\nWhite,\r\nRed,\r\nBlackish,\r\nPale buff','75370ccf4c03a9e8212b468ec13a1db1','538b2d011618ecc63870bdffba4a8499','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/24002443/DSCF5205.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/24002116/DSCF4835.jpg','https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.jonswanservices.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F24002316%2FDSCF5160-Enhanced-NR.jpg','Ruby-crowned kinglets live in a wide variety of habitats, including forests, woodlands, shrublands, and wetlands. In the summer, they are common in spruce-fir forests in northern North America and Canada, as well as in mixed woods, floodplain forests, and mountain-shrub habitats. In the winter, they move to lower elevations and can be found in many forest and shrub habitats','The ruby-crowned kinglet (Corthylio calendula) breeds in Alaska, Canada, and the western mountains, and migrates south to the southern and southwestern United States and Mexico for the winter. The breeding range extends from Alaska to Newfoundland, south to southern California and New Mexico, and to the Great Lakes region and northern New England. During the winter, the ruby-crowned kinglet can be found in the western and southeastern states south to southern Mexico. Some mountain populations in the West simply move to lower elevations during the cold months.',0),(10,'American Robin','American Robin','thrushes',7,'grey','orange','white','black',NULL,0,'grey','black','',1,'brown','c','c','c','c','m','Turdus migratorius','american_robin.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/06194559/DSCF2957.jpg',0,'Females are slight duller in color ','The American Robin (Turdus migratorius) is a familiar and widespread bird across North America, recognized by its orange-red breast, gray back and wings, and white lower belly and under-tail. As a member of the thrush family, it is known for its melodious song, which often heralds the arrival of spring. These medium-sized birds are adaptable and can thrive in a variety of habitats, including forests, gardens, and urban areas. American Robins are omnivores, primarily feeding on earthworms, insects, and berries. They are often seen hopping across lawns, tilting their heads to listen for worms underground. With their cheerful presence and vibrant song, American Robins hold a beloved place in North American culture and folklore.','The American Robin: An Emblem of Seasonal Change\r\n\r\nThe American robin (Turdus migratorius) is among the most recognizable and widespread bird species in North America. Its ubiquity across diverse habitats, distinctive plumage, and melodious song make it an emblem of the changing seasons and a subject of interest in ecological, behavioral, and conservation studies. This essay explores the American robin\'s taxonomy, habitat, behavior, role in ecosystems, and conservation status, shedding light on its significance beyond being a harbinger of spring.\r\n\r\nTaxonomy and Description\r\n\r\nThe American robin belongs to the thrush family (Turdidae), known for their melodious songs and includes species like the bluebird and the nightingale. It is characterized by a distinctive orange-red breast, a gray back, and a white lower belly and undertail coverts. Both sexes exhibit similar plumage, though females tend to have slightly duller colors. Juveniles can be identified by their speckled breasts, reminiscent of their European counterparts, which led to their name by early European settlers.\r\n\r\nHabitat and Distribution\r\n\r\nAdaptable and resilient, the American robin inhabits a wide range of environments, from forests and mountainous areas to urban parks and gardens across North America. Its distribution spans from the tundra of Canada and Alaska to the deserts of Mexico, showcasing its versatility in nesting and foraging in varied landscapes. The robin\'s presence in urban and suburban settings highlights its adaptability to human-altered environments, contributing to its widespread recognition and popularity.\r\n\r\nBehavior and Diet\r\n\r\nThe American robin exhibits a diverse diet that changes with the seasons. In spring and summer, its diet primarily consists of invertebrates, including earthworms, insects, and snails. During the colder months, it shifts to fruits and berries, playing a crucial role in the dispersal of numerous plant species. This dietary flexibility supports its ability to thrive in various habitats and climates.\r\n\r\nSocial behavior varies seasonally; robins are known for their communal winter roosts and more territorial behavior during the breeding season. Their song, a series of melodious whistles, is a familiar sound in North American landscapes, often associated with the arrival of spring.\r\n\r\n Role in Ecosystems\r\n\r\nAs both predator and prey, the American robin holds a significant place in the food web. Its predation on insects and other invertebrates helps control pest populations, benefiting agriculture and garden health. Moreover, as a prey species for hawks, cats, and larger mammals, it contributes to the biodiversity and balance of ecosystems.\r\n\r\nRobins are also important seed dispersers, aiding in the regeneration of many tree and shrub species. Their foraging habits influence the structure and composition of plant communities, underscoring their ecological importance.\r\n\r\nConservation Status\r\n\r\nCurrently, the American robin is listed as Least Concern by the IUCN Red List, reflecting its wide distribution and stable population sizes. However, it faces threats from habitat loss, pesticide use, and climate change, which could impact its food sources and migratory patterns. Conservation efforts focusing on habitat preservation, pollution reduction, and climate action are vital to ensuring the robin\'s continued abundance and ecological role.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\n\r\nThe American robin is more than a symbol of spring; it is a key player in North American ecosystems, contributing to pest control, seed dispersal, and biodiversity. Its widespread presence across the continent, adaptability to diverse habitats, and the joy it brings to observers underscore its importance in both natural and human-altered landscapes. As we move forward, it is imperative to recognize and mitigate the threats it faces, ensuring that the American robin continues to thrive for generations to come, heralding the change of seasons with its cheerful song.','Handsome,\r\nGallant,\r\nBold,\r\nHones,\r\nBright-eyed,\r\nSturdy,\r\nluck,\r\nhappiness,\r\nrebirth,\r\nThrush,\r\nUpright\r\n','3a2ad52a25ee2038c6578f26aaa37468','0','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/24100656/DSCF3286.jpg','','\r\nhttps:&#x2F;&#x2F;cdn.jonswanservices.com&#x2F;wp-content&#x2F;uploads&#x2F;2023&#x2F;12&#x2F;24101801&#x2F;DSCF7241-scaled.jpg','Robins live in a variety of habitats, including forests, woodlands, mountains, pastures, farmland, and human-dominated areas like parks, gardens, and urban areas. They can be found in open woodlands, marshes, fields, forest borders, orchards, hedges, gardens, and urban, suburban, rural yards, and parks.','\r\nAmerican robins (Turdus migratorius) are found in the United States and Canada, except for Hawaii and the northernmost parts of the two continents. Their summer range extends from Alaska, northern New England, and most of Canada to southern Mexico. Their winter range covers southern Canada to Guatemala, and some populations fly south for the winter to the southern U.S., Mexico, and Central America. However, many populations live in colder areas year-round, traveling based on wherever they can find food',0),(11,'Cedar Waxwing','Cedar Waxwing','pipits_waxwings',9,'brown','grey','yellow','','grey',0,'brown','black','',0,'brown','frequent','frequent','frequent','frequent ','m','bombycilla cedrorum','cedar_waxwing.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/28163435/cedar-waxwing-yellow-copy.jpg',0,'Males and females generally look alike, with the exception of the male\'s chin, which usually has a darker coloration than the female\'s chin.','The Cedar Waxwing (Bombycilla cedrorum) is a medium-sized, sleek bird characterized by its smooth, silky plumage of soft, grayish-brown colors, with a distinctive crest on its head. It has a black mask-like line through the eyes, a pale yellow belly, and a bright yellow tip on the tail. One of its most striking features is the small, red, wax-like droplets on the tips of its secondary feathers, which give the bird its name. Cedar Waxwings are sociable birds, often seen in large flocks, particularly during their non-breeding. season. They primarily feed on fruits and berries, but will also consume insects, especially when feeding their young. Cedar Waxwings are known for their nomadic lifestyle, moving unpredictably across their range in North America, depending on food availability.','A long description is a way to provide long alternative text for non-text elements, such as images. Generally, alternative text exceeding 250 characters, which cannot be made more concise without making it less descriptive or meaningful, should have a long description.','\r\n\r\nNoisy, \r\nLavish, \r\nSplendid, \r\nWinsome,\r\nslim, \r\nTrim, \r\nDandified, \r\nBeautiful, \r\nSilky, \r\nHeavenly','071005a0ec170655ca1dae0e5d3847b8','0','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/28163531/cedarwaxwingspair.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/28163435/cedar-waxwing-yellow-copy.jpg','https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.jonswanservices.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F28163550%2Fcedar-waxwing-copy.jpg','Cedar waxwings (Bombycilla cedrorum) live in a variety of habitats, including deciduous, coniferous, and mixed woodlands, as well as farms, orchards, suburban parks, and backyards. They are often found near streams, in old fields, grasslands, sagebrush, and along desert washes. They like areas with small trees and shrubs for nesting and food, and often nest in riparian areas, which have shrubs and trees for nesting and fruit and emerging aquatic insects','\r\n\r\nCedar waxwings (Bombycilla cedrorum) are found in North America, with their breeding range extending from southern Canada to the northern United States. Their winter range includes the United States, Mexico, Central America, and the Caribbean region, and some birds travel as far south as Panama and Costa Rica. Many birds in the northern United States and extreme southern Canada are year-round residents.',0),(12,'Spotted Towhee','Spotted Towhee','sparrows ',12,'black','orange','white',NULL,NULL,0,'black','black','',1,'red','common','common','common','frequent','m','Pipilo maculatus','spotted_towhee.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/01213205/9C306E49-8A80-421B-B62B-D965EBEDDF20.jpg',0,'Females have a grey head and is not as dark as the males. ','The Spotted Towhee is a bird species native to North America. It is a member of the sparrow family and is known for its distinctive black and white spotted plumage. The male has a black head, back, and tail, with white spots on its wings and back, while the female has a brownish-gray head and back with the same white spots. They are commonly found in brushy areas, woodlands, and suburban gardens.','The Spotted Towhee: A Beautiful Bird of North America\r\n\r\nThe Spotted Towhee is a beautiful bird that is native to North America. It is a member of the sparrow family and is known for its striking appearance and unique song. In this blog post, we will explore the characteristics of the Spotted Towhee, its habitat, diet, and behavior.\r\n\r\nCharacteristics of the Spotted Towhee\r\n\r\nThe Spotted Towhee is a medium-sized bird that measures about 7-8 inches in length. It has a black head, back, and tail, with white spots on its wings and back. Its underparts are a rusty-red color, and it has a white belly. The male and female have similar plumage, but the male has a brighter red color on its sides.\r\n\r\nHabitat of the Spotted Towhee\r\n\r\nThe Spotted Towhee is found throughout North America, from southern Alaska to Mexico. It prefers to live in dense shrubs and forests, especially those with a mix of deciduous and coniferous trees. It is also commonly found in suburban areas with large, well-established gardens and parks.\r\n\r\nDiet of the Spotted Towhee\r\n\r\nThe Spotted Towhee is primarily a ground feeder, and its diet consists of insects, seeds, and berries. It uses its strong beak to scratch through the leaf litter and soil to find food. It is also known to visit bird feeders, especially during the winter months when food is scarce.\r\n\r\nBehavior of the Spotted Towhee\r\n\r\nThe Spotted Towhee is a solitary bird, and it is often seen hopping along the ground or perching on low branches. It is a vocal bird and has a unique song that sounds like \"drink your tea.\" It is also known for its aggressive behavior towards other birds, especially during the breeding season.\r\n\r\nIn conclusion, the Spotted Towhee is a beautiful bird that is native to North America. It is known for its striking appearance, unique song, and aggressive behavior. If you are lucky enough to spot one in your backyard or on a hike, take a moment to appreciate its beauty and observe its behavior.','Noisy, Lavish, Splendid, Winsome, Grayish-brown, Slim, Trim, Dandified, Beautiful, Silky, and Heavenly','4c566c9ac3068a6ff7ddc009771af4f3','0','https://www.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/DSCF9045-Enhanced-NR.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/27120154/DSCF7329-copy.jpg','https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.jonswanservices.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2021%2F03%2F27120154%2FDSCF7329-copy.jpg','\r\nCedar Waxwing | Audubon Field Guide\r\nOpen woodlands, fruiting trees, orchards; in winter, widespread, including towns. Breeding habitat is influenced by availability of fruiting trees and shrubs, often most common in \"edge\" situations, as along forest edges, streamsides, overgrown fields, edges of swamps, suburban yards','Cedar waxwings are found year-round mostly in the northern half of the United States. Non-breeding winter populations are found from the Midwest and southern states down through Mexico, the Caribbean, Central America, and the northwestern reaches of Colombia.',0),(13,'Golden-Crowned Sparrow','Golden-Crowned-Sparrow','sparrows ',12,'grey','brown','','',NULL,0,'black','yellow','white',0,'brown','c','c','c','f','s','Zonotrichia atricapilla','golden_crowned_sparrow.jpg','https://www.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/female-golden-crowned-2.jpg',0,'females are slightly duller in color. During mating season, males have a brighter golden crown. \r\n','<p class=\"p1\">The Golden-crowned Sparrow (Zonotrichia atricapilla) is a striking bird native to the western parts of North America. Easily recognizable by its distinctive golden crown, bordered by black stripes, this medium-sized sparrow exhibits a blend of gray and brown plumage across its body, which provides excellent camouflage in its natural habitat. Adults typically display more vivid coloration during the breeding season, with males showcasing brighter gold and black crown markings than females.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\"> </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Golden-crowned Sparrows are primarily found in shrubby habitats and open woodlands, especially during their breeding season in Alaska and northwestern Canada. In the winter, they migrate southward to the western United States, where they can be found in a variety of settings including gardens, parks, and coastal areas. These birds have a melodious song, often described as a series of sad, sweet whistles, which adds to their allure among birdwatchers.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\"> </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Primarily ground feeders, their diet consists of seeds, fruits, and insects. The Golden-crowned Sparrow is a social bird outside of the breeding season, often forming flocks with other sparrows. Despite their beautiful appearance and enchanting songs, they are relatively shy and elusive, making any sighting a rewarding experience for bird enthusiasts.</p>','\r\nThe Golden Crown Sparrow (Zonotrichia atricapilla) is a captivating species of bird that belongs to the family Passerellidae. Renowned for its distinct golden crown and melodious song, this sparrow species serves as a fascinating subject for the study of avian adaptation and migration. Native to North America, particularly the western regions, the Golden Crown Sparrow exhibits unique behavioral and physiological adaptations that enable it to thrive across varying environments. This essay delves into the life cycle, migratory patterns, habitat preferences, and adaptive strategies of the Golden Crown Sparrow, highlighting its significance in avian ecology and conservation.\r\n\r\n Life Cycle and Migratory Patterns\r\n\r\nThe Golden Crown Sparrow embarks on a remarkable migratory journey that spans thousands of miles. Breeding primarily in the boreal forests and tundra of Alaska and Canada during the summer, these sparrows migrate to the western coast of the United States for wintering. This annual migration underscores the species\' adaptability to diverse climatic conditions and habitats.\r\n\r\nThe breeding season, commencing in late spring, is a critical period for the Golden Crown Sparrow. Males establish territories and attract females through their distinctive songs, which play a pivotal role in mate selection. Females construct nests on the ground, often concealed by vegetation, where they lay and incubate eggs. The care of the young involves both parents, showcasing a cooperative breeding strategy that enhances offspring survival.\r\n\r\n Habitat Preferences and Adaptation\r\n\r\nGolden Crown Sparrows exhibit a preference for habitats that offer ample cover and food resources. During the breeding season, they favor open tundra and shrubby areas, whereas winter habitats include chaparral, coastal scrub, and urban gardens. Such flexibility in habitat selection is indicative of the species\' adaptability to varying environmental conditions.\r\n\r\nAdaptations to cold environments are particularly noteworthy. The Golden Crown Sparrow\'s plumage provides insulation against frigid temperatures, enabling it to maintain body heat. Additionally, its diet shifts seasonally, from insects and arthropods in the summer to seeds and berries in the winter, reflecting an adaptive foraging strategy that ensures nutritional needs are met throughout the year.\r\n\r\n Conservation and Ecological Significance\r\n\r\nThe conservation status of the Golden Crown Sparrow is currently of least concern, according to the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN). However, habitat loss and climate change pose potential threats to its populations. Urbanization and agricultural expansion have led to the degradation of natural habitats, while shifting climatic patterns could impact migratory routes and breeding grounds.\r\n\r\nThe ecological role of the Golden Crown Sparrow is multifaceted. As seed dispersers and insect predators, these sparrows contribute to the maintenance of ecological balance within their habitats. Moreover, their migratory behavior offers insights into the effects of climate change on avian species, making them valuable indicators for ecological monitoring and research.\r\n\r\n Conclusion\r\n\r\nThe Golden Crown Sparrow stands as a testament to the resilience and adaptability of avian species. Through its annual migratory journey, diverse habitat preferences, and adaptive strategies, this sparrow navigates the challenges of changing environments. Understanding the life cycle, behaviors, and ecological role of the Golden Crown Sparrow not only enriches our knowledge of avian biology but also underscores the importance of conservation efforts to safeguard these remarkable birds and their habitats for future generations. As we continue to study and protect the Golden Crown Sparrow, we gain insights into the broader themes of adaptation, migration, and ecological balance in the natural world.','','79256777e6b524ec1b2f25e42d18bbe3','','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/09171412/golden-crownde2-1.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/09210516/DSCF9029-Enhanced-NR.jpg','https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jonswanservices.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F03%2Ffemale-golden-crowned-2.jpg','','',0),(14,'Dark-Eyed Junco','Dark-Eyed Junco','sparrows ',12,'grey','black','brown','white',NULL,0,'black','black','',1,'brown','c','c','c','c','s','junco hyemalis','dark_eyed_junco.jpg',NULL,1,'','The Dark-eyed Junco (Junco hyemalis) is a small, charismatic songbird that graces much of North America, especially during its winter migration. These birds are easily recognized by their distinctive markings: they typically have slate-gray or black heads and backs (the males being darker), with contrasting white bellies. What truly sets them apart, however, are their striking dark eyes, which stand out against their subdued plumage, and their white outer tail feathers, which flash distinctively during flight.\r\n\r\nDark-eyed Juncos are often referred to as \"snowbirds\" in some regions due to their appearance in backyards and bird feeders during the winter months, heralding the change of seasons. They exhibit a variety of plumage colorations across different geographic regions, leading to the identification of several subspecies, such as the Slate-colored, Oregon, Pink-sided, and White-winged Juncos, among others.\r\n\r\nThese adaptable birds can be found in a wide range of habitats, from forest edges and alpine meadows to suburban parks and gardens. They primarily feed on seeds and insects, foraging on the ground in small flocks. Dark-eyed Juncos are also known for their sweet, trilling songs and calls, adding a touch of joy to their surroundings regardless of the season.',NULL,'Curious,\r\nAgile,\r\nTrusting,\r\nAcbatic,\r\nMonogamous,\r\nIndustrious,\r\nGregarious,\r\nCheerful,\r\nInquisitive\r\n','','0','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/24095943/junco-scaled.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/27231604/DSCF5825.jpg','https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.jonswanservices.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2021%2F03%2F27231716%2FDSCF5831.jpg%0A','Black-capped chickadees are found in deciduous and mixed deciduous-evergreen forests, especially near forest edges. They are commonly found near willows and cottonwoods, and like to make their nests in the snags of alder and birch trees. Feeders and nest boxes can be used to attract chickadees to suburban backyards.','Black-capped chickadees (Parus atricapillus) are found from Alaska through the southern half of Canada and south to roughly half of the lower 48 U.S. states. In the West, their range extends as far south as New Mexico, while in the east, they follow the Appalachian Mountains south to Georgia',0),(15,'Song Sparrow','Song Sparrow','sparrows ',12,'greyish_brown','grey','brown',NULL,NULL,1,'brown','white','',0,'brown','f','f','f','f','s','Melospiza melodia','song_sparrow.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/29233627/song-sparrow-scaled.jpg',1,'Female song sparrows have a dusty brown head, while male song sparrows have a dark gray head with chestnut streaks','The song sparrow (Melospiza melodia) is a small, brown-streaked bird that is found throughout North America. It is a member of the Emberizidae family, which includes other sparrows, buntings, and towhees. The song sparrow is a common sight in backyards, parks, and other open areas. It is easily identified by its distinctive song, which is a series of short, musical trills.\r\n\r\nThe song sparrow is a ground-dwelling bird, preferring to forage for food on the ground or in low vegetation. Its diet consists of insects, seeds, and berries. It is also known to eat grains, such as corn and wheat, which it finds in agricultural fields. The song sparrow is an important seed disperser, helping to spread native plants throughout its range.\r\n\r\nThe song sparrow is a monogamous species, meaning that it forms a pair bond with one mate for the duration of the breeding season. The male song sparrow is territorial and will defend its territory from other males. The female builds the nest, which is usually a cup-shaped structure made of grasses and other plant material. The female lays three to five eggs, which are incubated for 11 to 14 days. The young fledge after 10 to 14 days.\r\n\r\nThe song sparrow is a resilient species, able to adapt to a variety of habitats. It is also a long-distance migrant, traveling south in the winter to warmer climates. Despite its adaptability, the song sparrow is threatened by habitat loss and fragmentation due to human development. It is also vulnerable to predation by cats, hawks, and other birds of prey.\r\n\r\nThe song sparrow is an important part of the North American ecosystem. Its presence in backyards and parks provides a source of beauty and joy to many people. Its song is a reminder of the beauty and complexity of nature. The song sparrow is a species worth protecting and preserving for future generations.','Song sparrows (Melospiza melodia) are found throughout North America, from Alaska and Canada to the southern United States and Mexico. They are medium-distance migrants, with some birds from northern Canada and far Alaska flying to Mexico and the southern United States for the winter. Birds from the northern United States may migrate, but usually don\'t go as far south as the birds from farther north. This pattern is called \"leapfrog migration\".','Russet-and-gray,\r\nStreaky,\r\nWhite underneath,\r\nDark streaking,\r\nDark brown spot,\r\nLong and slender bill,\r\nLong diffuse streaks,\r\nBeautiful and distinct call,\r\nSmooth round heads,\r\nRounded wings\r\n\r\n','778bf277062f2d1aa038fa0dd2e1e5af','0','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/22200705/DSCF7998-scaled.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/22201309/DSCF8014-scaled.jpg','https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.jonswanservices.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2022%2F02%2F22201607%2FDSCF8021-scaled.jpg','Tidal marshes, Arctic grasslands, Desert scrub, Pinyon pine forests, Aspen parklands, Prairie shelterbelts, Pacific rain forest, Chaparral, Agricultural fields, and Overgrown pastures','Song sparrows (Melospiza melodia) are found throughout North America, from Alaska and Canada to the southern United States and Mexico. They are medium-distance migrants, with some birds from northern Canada and far Alaska flying to Mexico and the southern United States for the winter. Birds from the northern United States may migrate, but usually don\'t go as far south as the birds from farther north. This pattern is called \"leapfrog migration\"',0),(16,'American Goldfinch','American Goldfinch','finches',16,'yellow','yellow','white','brown',NULL,1,'yellow','white','',1,'brown','c','c','c','c','s','spinus tristis','american_goldfinch.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/02131907/DSCF0975-scaled-1.jpg',0,'The female has a more muted yellow color with brownish-gray wings.','A goldfinch is a small bird with bright yellow and black feathers. It is a common bird found in North America and Europe, and is known for its distinctive song and acrobatic flight. The male goldfinch has a bright yellow body with black wings and a black cap, while the female has a more muted yellow color with brownish-gray wings. Goldfinches are often seen feeding on thistle and other seeds, and are popular among birdwatchers and backyard bird enthusiasts.','The American goldfinch (Spinus tristis) is a small finch with a sharply pointed bill, short tail, and long wings. It\'s about the size of a sparrow, measuring 4.3–5.1 in (11–13 cm) long, weighing 0.4–0.7 oz (11–20 g), and with a wingspan of 7.5–8.7 in (19–22 cm). n spring and early summer, adult males are bright yellow with black foreheads, black wings with white markings, and white patches above and below the tail. In winter, they are drab, buffy-brown. Adult females are olive above and duller yellow beneath, with two distinct wingbars. \nGoldfinches are active and acrobatic, and can be found in weedy fields, cultivated areas, roadsides, orchards, and backyards. They live in open woodlands and eat seeds, and often climb about acrobatically on plants such as thistles to reach the seeds. They are most abundant in areas with thistle plants and near feeders, and their flight call sounds like \"po-ta-to-chip\". \nGoldfinches are very sociable birds, often breeding in loose groups. They have a delightful twittering song and call. ','streaky, brown, white, red-brown, slaty gray, small, familiar, common, thick, attractive, and variable','','0','0','','https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.jonswanservices.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F03%2F01235118%2Fgold-finch.jpeg%0A','Tidal marshes, Arctic grasslands, Desert scrub, Pinyon pine forests, Aspen parklands, Prairie shelterbelts, Pacific rain forest, Chaparral, Agricultural fields, and Overgrown pastures','The range of the Song Sparrow is continuous from the Aleutians to the eastern United States. There\'s also an isolated population that lives on the plateau of central Mexico, about 900 miles from the next closest population. These Song Sparrows have white throats and chests with black streaks.',0),(17,'House Finch','House Finch','finches',16,'grey','brown',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,'greyish_brown ','red','',0,'brown','c','c','c','c','s','Haemorhous mexicanus','house_finch.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/18095359/DSCF7090-scaled.jpg',0,'Females are greyish-brown unlike males that have additional red coloring.','<p class=\"p1\">House Finches (Haemorhous mexicanus) are small, brightly colored birds that are a common sight across much of North America. Originally native to the southwestern United States and Mexico, their range expanded dramatically in the 20th century after caged birds were released in New York in the 1940s. They have adapted well to human-altered environments and are often found in urban and suburban areas, as well as in wilder habitats like deserts and forests.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Males are easily recognizable by their vibrant red plumage on the head, throat, and breast, which can sometimes vary to orange or yellow, while females and young birds are more subdued in color, with streaky brown plumage that provides excellent camouflage. House Finches are about 5 to 6 inches in length, with a robust body and a short, conical bill that is well-suited for their primarily seed-based diet, although they also consume insects.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">These birds are gregarious outside of the breeding season, often forming large flocks. They have a cheerful, warbling song and a variety of calls, which they use to communicate with each other. House Finches are monogamous for the breeding season, and pairs can be quite affectionate, with the male often seen feeding the female as part of their courtship.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">House Finches build their nests in a variety of locations, from trees and shrubs to various nooks and crannies on buildings, showing their adaptability. They can produce several broods per year, with clutches typically consisting of 2 to 6 eggs.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">While their proliferation has been a success story in terms of their adaptability, House Finches have also faced challenges such as diseases like conjunctivitis, which can spread rapidly through populations. Nonetheless, they remain common and beloved visitors to backyard feeders, where they add a splash of color and song.</p>','\r\n  <style type=\"text/css\">\r\n    p.p1 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; font: 13.0px \'Helvetica Neue\'; min-height: 15.0px}\r\n    p.p2 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; font: 13.0px \'Helvetica Neue\'}\r\n  </style>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\">The House Finch (Haemorhous mexicanus) is a small, yet vibrant and resilient bird species that has garnered attention for its remarkable adaptability and successful colonization of diverse habitats, especially urban environments. Originally confined to the western United States and Mexico, the House Finch has expanded its range dramatically, becoming a common sight in cities, suburbs, and rural areas across much of North America. This essay explores the biological and ecological aspects of the House Finch, including its physical characteristics, behavior, diet, reproductive habits, and notably, its adaptation and expansion into urban settings, shedding light on the factors contributing to its success in these environments.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\">Physical Characteristics and Behavior</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\">The House Finch is easily recognizable by its bright red plumage in males and more subdued brown streaks in females, making it a favorite among birdwatchers. Measuring approximately 5 to 6 inches in length, these birds exhibit a strong sexual dimorphism, not only in color but also in their songs, which males use to attract mates. Their diet primarily consists of grains, seeds, and fruits, allowing them to thrive in a variety of settings, including human-modified landscapes where such food sources are abundant.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\">Reproductive Habits</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\">House Finches are prolific breeders, with their breeding season extending from March to August. They are known for their flexible nesting habits, often building nests in a variety of structures, including trees, shrubs, and even man-made objects, such as building ledges and hanging planters. This adaptability in nesting preferences underscores their ability to thrive in urban areas. A single pair can produce several broods per season, with each clutch containing 2 to 6 eggs, contributing to their rapid population growth and expansion.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\">Adaptation and Expansion into Urban Environments</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\">The remarkable expansion of the House Finch across North America, particularly into urban areas, can be attributed to several key factors. Firstly, their generalist diet makes them well-suited to environments where human activity provides an abundance of food resources. Secondly, their adaptability in nesting allows them to exploit a variety of urban structures for reproduction. Additionally, the warmth provided by urban settings may create microclimates that are favorable for their survival during colder months, reducing mortality and supporting year-round populations.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\">Urbanization typically poses significant challenges to wildlife due to habitat destruction, pollution, and increased competition for resources. However, the House Finch\'s success story is indicative of their exceptional ability to exploit new opportunities presented by urban landscapes. This adaptability raises important considerations for urban planning and wildlife management, highlighting the need for strategies that support biodiversity and the coexistence of human and wildlife populations in shared environments.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\">Conclusion</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\">The House Finch serves as a compelling example of how certain species can flourish in the face of rapid environmental changes, including urbanization. Their vibrant presence in cities and towns across North America not only adds color and life to these settings but also provides valuable lessons on adaptability, resilience, and the complex interactions between humans and wildlife. As we continue to shape our urban landscapes, understanding and supporting the ecological dynamics that allow species like the House Finch to thrive is crucial for fostering sustainable communities that embrace biodiversity as a cornerstone of urban life.</p>\r\n','','89cd5ba5d6bf911333e3bd88cb55e3b4','','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/24102157/DSCF5914-1024x576.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/10230132/DSCF0643-scaled.jpg','https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.jonswanservices.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2022%2F03%2F10230353%2FDSCF0650-scaled.jpg','House finches are native to open and desert habitats, but have expanded their range to almost any human-altered habitat. They can be found in a wide range of habitats, from arid deserts to open woodlands and shrubby fields. House finches are familiar birds of human-created habitats including buildings, lawns, small conifers, and urban centers. In rural areas, you can also find House Finches around barns and stables.','House finches (Carpodacus mexicanus) are found in a wide range of habitats across North America, including urban and suburban areas, arid deserts, open woodlands, and shrubby fields. They are common in the U.S., parts of Canada, and Mexico, and extend from the southern edge of Canada through central and southern Mexico.',0),(18,'Lesser Goldfinch','Lesser Goldfinch','finches',16,'yellow','grey','brown',NULL,NULL,0,'yellow','white','',0,'black','common','common','common','common','s','Spinus psaltria','lesser_goldfinch.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/22220904/DSCF3886.jpg',0,'\r\nFemales and immatures have olive backs, dull yellow underparts, and black wings marked by two whitish wingbars.','The Lesser Goldfinch (Spinus psaltria) is a small, brightly colored songbird that is part of the finch family. It measures about 4 to 5 inches in length and displays sexual dimorphism in its plumage. Males are easily identified by their vibrant yellow underparts and black or dark green back, wings, and tail, along with a black cap on their head. Females and juveniles, on the other hand, have more subdued coloring, primarily olive or grayish, with lighter yellow underparts.\r\n\r\nLesser Goldfinches are found throughout the western United States, Mexico, and parts of Central America. They inhabit a variety of environments, including open woodlands, gardens, and areas with scattered trees and shrubs. These birds are adaptable, often visiting bird feeders in residential areas.\r\n\r\nTheir diet mainly consists of seeds, particularly those of sunflowers and other members of the Aster family, but they will also consume insects occasionally. The Lesser Goldfinch is known for its pleasant, tinkling song and can often be seen in small flocks, especially outside of the breeding season.','The lesser goldfinch is a small songbird with a short, conical bill, notched tail, and long, pointed wings. It\'s about the size of an American goldfinch, with an average length of 3.5–4.7 in (9–12 cm) and weight of 0.28–0.41 oz (8–11.5 g). The lesser goldfinch has white patches on its wings and tail, and its back can be solid glossy black or dull green. During breeding season, the male establishes his territory by calling and singing from atop tall trees. He then gives courtship calls to attract a female into his territory. The female builds most of the nest over 4 to 8 days, collecting plant materials such as leaves, bark, catkins, cocoons and spiderwebs in her bill. She weaves these together into a cup and then lines the nest with hair, feathers, wool, rabbit fur, or cottonseed fibers. \nLesser goldfinches are uncommon and local residents in the east, and are often seen in small flocks feeding along brushy roadsides, particularly where thistle grows. They cling to the seed heads of tall plants, bending the stem down so that it can end up hanging upside down while picking at the seeds. These birds will also eat flowers and buds from trees such as cottonwood and some berries. ','','dfa7251d02fda3a921ae8aa0c55e2b8e','0','','','https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.jonswanservices.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F03%2F01235650%2Flesser-gold.jpg','Lesser Goldfinch | Audubon Field Guide\r\nOpen brushy country, open woods, wooded streams, gardens. Generally in semi-open areas, where there are thickets and trees close to open weedy fields, from low valleys to high in mountains. In dry country, usually found close to water. In the tropics, found in semi-open terrain, woodland edges.','Lesser goldfinches (Carduelis psaltria) live in patchy open habitats, including woodlands, scrublands, forest clearings, farmlands, and desert oases. They can be found from the western U.S. to South America, in scrubby oak, cottonwood, and willow habitats, and in suburban yards. They also live in semi-open areas, where there are thickets and trees close to open weedy fields, from low valleys to high in mountains. In dry country, they are usually found close to water',0),(19,'Anna\'s Hummingbirds','Anna\'s Hummingbird','swifts_hummingbirds',17,'green','grey','red',NULL,NULL,0,'green','brown','grey',0,'brown','c','c','c','c','t','Calypte anna','anna\'s_hummingbird.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/08204427/DSCF7438-Enhanced-NR.jpg',0,'females are duller in color and are mostly a mix of grey and green. Females do not have the  the iridescent gorget, that extends to the crown of the head of males.','<p class=\"p1\">Anna\'s hummingbirds (Calypte anna) are a species of hummingbird native to the west coast of North America, ranging from British Columbia in Canada down through California and into parts of Mexico. In the springtime, these tiny, vibrant birds become particularly active, engaging in a variety of behaviors that are fascinating to observe. Here are some highlights of Anna\'s hummingbirds in the spring:</p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><b><span class=\"Apple-converted-space\"> </span>Breeding Season</b></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Spring marks the beginning of the breeding season for Anna\'s hummingbirds. They are among the earliest birds to start the breeding process, sometimes as early as December or January, but activities peak in the spring.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><b>Courtship Displays</b></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Male Anna\'s hummingbirds perform spectacular courtship displays to attract females. One of the most notable is the \"dive display,\" where the male flies up to 130 feet into the air and then dives down at high speeds towards the female, making a loud popping sound with their tail feathers at the bottom of the dive. This display is not only a visual spectacle but also an auditory one.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><b>Nesting</b></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Female Anna\'s hummingbirds are responsible for building the nest and caring for the young. They construct their nests from plant down, spider webs, and other materials, making them stretchy and sturdy. The nests are often located on tree branches or in shrubs. The female lays usually two eggs, which she incubates for about 14-19 days.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><b><span class=\"Apple-converted-space\"> </span>Feeding</b></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">In the spring, Anna\'s hummingbirds feed on nectar from flowers and flowering trees, using their long tongues to reach into flowers. They play a vital role in pollination. They also eat insects and spiders, especially during the breeding season, to meet their high protein needs.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><b>Territorial Behavior</b></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Anna\'s hummingbirds can be quite territorial, especially in areas where food sources are abundant. Males aggressively defend their territory to ensure they have enough resources to attract and support a mate.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><b>Adaptations to Urban Environments</b></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Interestingly, Anna\'s hummingbirds have adapted well to urban environments. They are commonly seen in gardens and parks, where hummingbird feeders and a variety of flowering plants provide ample food sources. This adaptation has helped them to thrive, even as some natural habitats are under threat.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Observing Anna\'s hummingbirds in the spring can be a rewarding experience for bird watchers and nature lovers. Their vibrant colors, dynamic behaviors, and the sounds of their courtship displays add a layer of excitement to the natural world as it awakens from the winter.</p>',NULL,'vibrant,agile,tiny,energetic,resilent,colorful,graceful,bold,fast,beautiful','b87718aceda39459c9f22bb4993a1dc0','72a5e45dac91331c5c9476f94f60d855','https://www.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/DSCF8727-1.jpg','https://www.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/DSCF8750.jpg','https://www.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/DSCF8726-Enhanced-NR-1.jpg','\r\nAnna\'s hummingbirds (Calypte anna) live in a variety of habitats, including urban and suburban areas, chaparral, coastal scrub, oak savannahs, and open woodland. They are most common in lowlands and lower mountain slopes, but may wander to high mountain meadows in late summer.','The Anna\'s hummingbird (Calypte anna) is a year-round resident of the Pacific coast, ranging from southern Alaska to northern Baja California, and inland to southern and central Arizona, extreme southern Nevada and southeastern Utah, and western Texas. Their range has expanded greatly since the mid-1930s, likely due to their effective use of nonnative plants and feeders in urban and suburban areas.',0),(20,'Say\'s Phoebe','Say\'s Phoebe','flycatchers',18,'grey','greyish_brown ','black','orange',NULL,0,'greyish_brown ','brown','',1,NULL,'o','o','u','u',NULL,'Sayornis Saya','says\'s_phoebe.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/10232350/DSCF0777-scaled.jpg',1,'Male Say\'s Phoebes are usually larger than females, and their plumage is often darker. However, these characteristics aren\'t always reliable indicators of the bird\'s sex.\r\n','<p class=\"p1\">The Say\'s phoebe has a brownish gray back, cinnamon belly, gray breast, and blackish tail. It is larger than a Dark-eyed Junco, but smaller than an American Robin, measuring 6.7 in (17 cm) long and weighing 0.7-0.8 oz (21-22 g). It can raise its head feathers into a small peak at the back.\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The Say\'s phoebe is found year-round from western Colorado, southwest to southern California, east to the western panhandle of Texas and south through western Mexico. It breeds from Alaska south through western and south central Canada, south through North Dakota, the midwest and to New Mexico and westward.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The Say\'s phoebe is often found in deserts, where its cinnamon-washed bellies help it blend in. It can be quite vocal, making a clear, slurred whistle and a burry, hiccupping note. It can also be quiet and difficult to detect.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><br></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The Say\'s phoebe eats insects and builds nests in buildings. You can attract a pair by putting up a shelf attached to a building well before breeding season.','Say\'s Phoebes are found in grasslands, often in deserts, where their cinnamon-washed bellies help them blend in. They can be quite vocal, making a clear, slurred whistle and a burry, hiccupping note. They can also be quiet and difficult to detect. \r\nSay\'s Phoebes eat insects and build nests in buildings. They may use your backyard to catch insects or build a nest under the eaves of your house. You can attract a pair by putting up a shelf attached to a building well before breeding season. \r\nSay\'s Phoebes eat almost entirely insects, including wild bees, wasps, winged ants, beetles, moths, grasshoppers, crickets, and dragonflies. They also eat spiders and millipedes, and occasionally eat berries.The genus name Sayornis comes from the specific part of Charles Lucien Bonaparte\'s name for Say\'s phoebe, Muscicapa saya, and the Ancient Greek word ornis, which means \"bird\". \"Phoebe\" is also an alternative name for the Roman moon-goddess Diana, and it may have been chosen to imitate the bird\'s call. \r\n\r\nSay\'s Phoebe is named after Thomas Say, an American naturalist who first encountered the bird in 1819 at a site near Cañon City, Colorado. Say\'s Phoebe\'s friend, Charles Bonaparte, the nephew of Napoleon, named the bird after Say','Medium-sized, Long-tailed, Gray-brown, Cinnamon-washed, Black-tailed, Black-billed, Pale-winged, Salmon-pink, White-bellied, White-egged, Burry, Hiccupping, Vocal, Quiet, Cryptic, Widespread, Numerous, and Least concern',NULL,'','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/10232518/DSCF0826-scaled.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/10232518/DSCF0826-scaled.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/10232645/DSCF1010-1-scaled.jpg','Dry, open areas with few plants, such as sagebrush flats, badlands, canyons, and desert borders. They can also be found in grasslands, savannas, ranches, farmlands, and urban and suburban habitats. They avoid forested areas','The Say\'s Phoebe\'s breeding range extends from central Mexico to the Arctic tundra, and may even follow the Alaska pipeline north to nest on it. It breeds in open, arid country at elevations ranging from 300 to 1800 meters, between late March and late August',0),(21,'Red-Winged Blackbird','Red-Winged Blackbird','Icteridae',14,'black','red','yellow',NULL,NULL,0,'black','black','',1,'black','common','common ','common','frequent','m','Agelaius phoeniceus','redwinged-blackbird.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/03185941/DSCF3456.jpg',0,'female blackbirds are brown with brown beaks and streaks or spots on their breasts. They have a dark brown upper body with a paler, streaky lower body. Their feathers have a slightly reddish-brown tinge, especially on the wings and tail. The yellow of the beak and eyelid ring is more distinct than in young blackbirds, but not as intense as in males','The red-winged blackbird (Agelaius phoeniceus) is a medium-sized songbird with glossy black feathers and red patches on its shoulders. The patches, also known as epaulets, are visible when the bird is resting and flash while it flies. The male\'s shoulder patches are distinctive, and he can puff them up or hide them depending on how confident he is. Immature males may have red shoulder patches that are sooty-brown and appear mottled. Females are brownish and have streaked breasts. \r\n','Red-winged blackbirds (Agelaius phoeniceus) are medium-sized birds with glossy black plumage and red patches on the males\' shoulders, called epaulets. The females have brown feathers with creamy white streaks and paler undersides, and sometimes have a whitish eyebrow They\'re an even glossy black with red-and-yellow shoulder badges. Females are crisply streaked and dark brownish overall, paler on the breast and often show a whitish eyebrow. Male Red-winged Blackbirds do everything they can to get noticed, sitting on high perches and belting out their conk-la-ree! song all day long.','Feisty and familiar','7b68eaec9a47b4a78118d4c41930dae6','','','','https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.jonswanservices.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2021%2F04%2F13235630%2Fredwinged-best-scaled.jpeg','Red-winged blackbirds (Agelaius phoeniceus) live in marshes, meadows, prairies, and fields near ponds year-round. They prefer wet places like fresh or saltwater marshes, rice paddies, cattail marshes, and telephone wires during breeding season. They may also be found in drier places like sedge meadows, alfalfa fields, and fallow fields. In winter, they are found in open fields and croplands. Some populations are year-round residents in the U.S., while others are short-distance migrants within North America. Only northern populations will migrate as far south as Mexico for the winte','Resident or short-distance migrant. Red-winged Blackbirds in northern North America winter in the southern United States, as far as about 800 miles from their breeding ranges.',1),(22,'White Breasted Nut Hatch','White Breasted Nut Hatch','nuthatches_creepers',5,'white','grey','black',NULL,NULL,0,'white','grey','black',0,'black','common','uncommon ','frequent','frequent ','s','Sitta carolinensis','white_breasted_nuthatch.jpg','',1,'Female white-breasted nuthatches look similar to males, but have a grayer cap and a slightly lighter crown. The female\'s crown is not quite black, so you can see the subtle difference where it meets the nape at close range. The female\'s cap is a bit paler than her nape patc','The white-breasted nuthatch (Sitta carolinensis) is a small, active bird with black, gray, and white markings. It\'s about the size of a robin or sparrow, with a short tail, thin bill, and beady black eye. White-breasted nuthatches have black crowns on their heads, white cheeks, and white undersides. Their backs are bluish-gray, and their wings and tails are a mixture of white, black, and bluish-gray. Males tend to be slightly more brightly colored than females','The white-breasted nuthatch (Sitta carolinensis) is a small, active bird with black, gray, and white markings. It\'s about the size of a robin or sparrow, with a short tail, thin bill, and beady black eye. White-breasted nuthatches have black crowns on their heads, white cheeks, and white undersides. Their backs are bluish-gray, and their wings and tails are a mixture of white, black, and bluish-gray. Males tend to be slightly more brightly colored than femalesWhite-breasted nuthatches are common feeder birds that live in arroyos, canyons, forests, woodlands, high mountains, and urban and suburban habitats. They\'re often found in older deciduous woodlands, but also in parks, wooded suburbs, and yards. \r\nWhite-breasted nuthatches get their name from their habit of jamming large nuts and acorns into tree bark, then whacking them with their sharp bill to “hatch” out the seed from the inside. They are also known for their loud, insistent nasal yammering. \r\nWhite-breasted nuthatches are protected under the Migratory Bird Treaty Act of 1918, to which Canada, Mexico, and the United States are all signatories.','  active, agile little birds with an appetite for insects and large, meaty seeds','23f564af936362e9f6f90937f72cc7ea','','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/24101012/nuthatch-scaled.jpg','','https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.jonswanservices.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F24101019%2Fnuthatch2-scaled.jpg','','',1),(23,'Red-Breasted Nuthatch','Red-Breasted Nuthatch ','nuthatches_creepers',5,'grey','orange','white',NULL,NULL,0,'white ','grey ','orange',0,'brown ','uncommon','uncommon','uncommon','uncommon','s','Sitta canadensis','red_breasted_nuthatch.jpg',NULL,0,'Females of any age can be distinguished from males by their paler slate-coloured crown,','The red-breasted nuthatch (Sitta canadensis) is a small, energetic bird with a distinctive black-and-white head pattern, blue-gray upperparts, and an orangey belly. Males have a black crown, white eyebrow, and black eyeline, while females have grayer caps and paler rusty underparts. Red-breasted nuthatches are 4.3 inches (11 cm) long, weigh 0.3-0.5 ounces (8-13 g), and have a wingspan of 7.1-7.9 inches (18-20 cm)','Red-breasted nuthatches are found in the north woods and western mountains, living in coniferous forests of spruce, fir, pine, hemlock, larch, and western red cedar. They also live in deciduous woods, including aspen, birch, poplar, oak, maple, and basswood. They prefer spruce-fir forests and live mostly on the branches of trees instead of on the trunks. \r\nRed-breasted nuthatches have strong feet, toes, and long, curved claws that allow them to climb down trees headfirst, or to clamber upside-down along the undersides of branches. They are also known for their tinny-sounding call, which is often heard before they are seen. \r\nRed-breasted nuthatches are aggressive birds that can sometimes dominate larger birds at feeders. They eat both insects and seeds, with spiders being on the menu in the summer and many seeds, especially those of conifers, in the winter. ','',NULL,'','','','','Red-breasted nuthatches (Sitta canadensis) mainly live in coniferous forests, especially those with spruce and fir, but can also be found in mixed-wood regions. They prefer to live among spruce, fir, pine, hemlock, larch, and western red cedar, as well as around aspens and poplars. In northeastern North America, they can also be found in forests of oak, hickory, maple, and birch. Eastern populations use more deciduous woods, including aspen, birch, poplar, oak, maple, and basswood. During irruptive winters, nuthatches may use habitats such as orchards, scrub, parks, plantations, and shade trees','The red-breasted nuthatch (Sitta canadensis) breeds in coniferous forests across Canada, Alaska, and the northeastern and western United States. Its breeding range extends from Alaska to Newfoundland and Labrador, south through the Great Lakes region, northern New England, and also in the higher elevations of the Appalachians to eastern Tennessee and North Carolina.',1),(24,'Townsend\'s Warbler','Townsend\'s Warbler','wood_warblers',10,'yellow','black','grey ','white','',0,'yellow','black','grey',0,'brown','uncommon','uncommon','uncommon','uncommon','m','Setophaga townsendi','townsend_warbler.jpg','',0,'','The Townsend\'s warbler (Setophaga townsendi) is a bird that breeds in coniferous forests from southern Alaska and northwestern Canada to the Pacific Northwest region of the United States. Most Townsend\'s warblers are migratory, with different populations wintering in two separate areas. They are difficult to see because they nest and forage high in the trees, but can be easier to see during migration and in winter, when they use almost any well-vegetated habitat','The Townsend\'s Warbler (Setophaga townsendi) is a medium-sized wood warbler with bold plumage. It has a black throat, yellow chest, and white wing bars, with streaked sides. The male has a bright yellow face with a black stripe across its cheeks, extending into an ear patch. The female has a dark cap and a yellow throat. Immature birds are similar to females with a dark green cap and cheeks. \r\nThe Townsend\'s Warbler is about the size of a Robin, with a length of 4.7-5.0 in (12-12.7 cm) and a wingspan of 7.5-8.3 in (19-21 cm). It weighs about 0.3-0.4 oz (7.3-10.4 g). \r\nThe Townsend\'s Warbler breeds in mature coniferous and mixed forests, and nests and forages high in the trees. It\'s difficult to see, but can be easier to see during migration and in winter, when it uses almost any well-vegetated habitat. In winter, it often investigates backyard feeders for energy-rich foods such as mealworms, peanut butter, and suet. ','','3c8bf677ecdc49a7a54da9de8af9b031','','','','https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.jonswanservices.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F04%2F05111717%2Ftownsend.jpg','Coniferous forests: Townsend\'s warblers prefer mature, dense stands of at least 20 acres. They breed in coniferous forests, and can be found in mixed flocks with chickadees, kinglets, and other warblers outside of the breeding season.\r\nPacific Coast: Townsend\'s warblers winter along the Pacific Coast.\r\nMexican and Central American highlands: Townsend\'s warblers winter in Mexican and Central American highlands.\r\nWell-vegetated habitats: Townsend\'s warblers use almost any well-vegetated habitat during migration, including orchards, juniper-oak woodlands, aspen forests, riparian cottonwoods, gardens, parks, and oases.\r\nBackyard feeders: In winter, Townsend\'s warblers often investigate backyard feeders for energy-rich foods such as mealworms, peanut butter, and sue','ownsend\'s Warblers breed in coniferous forests from southern Alaska and northwestern Canada south into the Pacific Northwest region of the United States. Most are migratory, with different populations of the species wintering in two separate areas',0),(25,'Violet Green Swallow','Violet-Green Swallow','swallows',3,'green','white','grey',NULL,NULL,0,'green','white','grey',0,'black','uncommon','occasional ','uncommon','rare','s','Tachycineta thalassina','violet_green_swallow.jpg',NULL,0,'Sleek songbird with a small head and tiny bill. Adult females are drabber than males with a brown cap and paler green backs, though some females can be nearly as bright as males. Note dusky cheek patch.','The violet-green swallow is a small North American passerine bird in the swallow family. These aerial insectivores are distributed along the west coast from Alaska to Mexico, extending as far east as Montana and Texas\r\n','The Violet-green Swallow is a small, iridescent gem of the western skies. Though often appearing dark at first glance, sunlight transforms them into miniature marvels. Their backs shimmer with a vibrant green sheen, while their rumps boast a stunning iridescent purple. A splash of white graces their cheeks and underparts, creating a striking contrast against their dark wings.\r\nKey Features:\r\nSize: Slightly smaller than a Barn Swallow, about 5.5 inches long.\r\nColor: Iridescent green back, purple rump, white face and underparts.\r\nFlight: Agile and acrobatic, often seen performing aerial stunts over water bodies.\r\nHabitat: Open woodlands, mountains, and meadows.\r\nDiet: Aerial insectivores, feeding on flying insects like flies, wasps, and beetles.\r\nMigration: Spends summers in western North America, winters in Mexico and Central America.\r\nWhere to find them in Portland: During the summer months, you might spot these dazzling birds flitting through the skies of Southwest Portland, especially near parks and open spaces with water bodies. Look for their acrobatic displays and flashes of iridescent color against the blue sky.\r\nBonus Fact: The Violet-green Swallow holds the record for the highest altitude bird banding ever recorded, at a staggering 29,029 feet!','small, streamlined songbirds with long, pointed wings, short tails, and tiny, flat bills',NULL,'','','','','The vibrant Violet-green Swallow thrives in open spaces near water, favoring woodlands, meadows, mountains, and even towns during breeding season. They\'re particularly drawn to areas with standing dead trees containing natural cavities like woodpecker holes, which they readily utilize for nesting.','The tree swallow breeds in the US and Canada. It winters along southern US coasts south, along the Gulf Coast, to Panama and the northwestern coast of South America, and in the West Indies.',1),(26,'Varied Thrush','Varied Thrush ','thrushes',7,'black ','orange','grey',NULL,NULL,0,'black','orange','grey',0,'uncommon','uncommon','uncommon','uncommon','uncommon','m','Ixoreus naevius','varied_thrush.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/04225939/test.jpg',0,'Female varied thrushes (ixoreus naevius) are paler than male varied thrushes, with a browner back and a fainter gray breast band. They also have a similar pattern to males, but with duller colors.','The varied thrush (Ixoreus naevius) is a stocky songbird with a rounded head, straight bill, and long legs. It\'s about the size of an American robin and smaller than a Steller\'s jay. The varied thrush has a bold pattern of black, blue, brown, gray, and orange. Males have a black breast band, orange eyebrow, and orange markings on the wings. Females have a similar pattern, but duller','The varied thrush (Ixoreus naevius) is a stocky songbird with a rounded head, straight bill, and long legs. It\'s about the size of an American robin and smaller than a Steller\'s jay. The varied thrush has a bold pattern of black, blue, brown, gray, and orange. Males have a black breast band, orange eyebrow, and orange markings on the wings. Females have a similar pattern, but dullerThe varied thrush lives in the dense, humid forests of the Pacific Northwest. It breeds in mature, wet forests and sings a slow, haunting series of long notes during breeding season. In the winter, it moves south of its breeding range and often visits feeders and yards. It eats seeds from ground feeders and can be attracted to yards with native fruiting shrubs. \r\nThe varied thrush has a simple, sweet, and echoing song. It sings two or three buzzy whistles, each drawn out until it fades away, followed by a short silence. The male Varied Thrush sings in whistled tones from the tops of live conifers, mainly in the morning and evening','',NULL,'','','','','Because Varied Thrush live in mature and old-growth forests containing very large trees and tend to live in forest patches larger than about 40 acres, logging and forest fragmentation can cause habitat loss that reduces their numbers.','The varied thrush is a short-distance migrant that lives in the wet forests of the Pacific Coast from Alaska to California. In the fall, they retreat to lower elevations and visit city parks and backyards. They are also known to wander outside of their normal range, sometimes as far as the East Coast',0),(27,'White-Crowned Sparrow','White-Crowned Sparrow','sparrows',12,'brown','grey','black','white',NULL,0,'grey','black','white',0,'black','uncommon','occasional','uncommon','occasional ','s','Zonotrichia leucophrys','white_crowned_sparrow.jpg',NULL,1,'Male and female white-crowned sparrows look the same, with black-and-white head stripes, gray breasts, and orange bills','The white-crowned sparrow (Zonotrichia leucophrys) is a medium-sized North American bird with a gray face and black and white stripes on its upper head. It has a long tail, small bill, and can be 5.9–6.3 in (15–16 cm) long, 0.9–1.0 oz (25–28 g) in weight, and have a wingspan of 8.3–9.4 in (21–24 cm). Its underparts are plain grayish without streaks, and its bill color varies from yellow to pink, but is always brighter than the white-throated sparrow.','The white-crowned sparrow (Zonotrichia leucophrys) is a medium-sized North American bird with a gray face and black and white stripes on its upper head. It has a long tail, small bill, and can be 5.9–6.3 in (15–16 cm) long, 0.9–1.0 oz (25–28 g) in weight, and have a wingspan of 8.3–9.4 in (21–24 cm). Its underparts are plain grayish without streaks, and its bill color varies from yellow to pink, but is always brighter than the white-throated sparrow.White-crowned sparrows are winter birds in much of the United States, arriving in September and can be found in fields, along roadsides, in low foliage at trail edges, or in your yard. They are not found on the West Coast or in the mountains of the West. \r\nWhite-crowned sparrows eat sunflower and other seeds, and they may also eat seeds dropped by other birds. You can encourage them to spend more time in your yard by making a brush pile. \r\nWhite-crowned sparrows breed in brushy areas or thickets in open forests, often with conifers. In migration and winter, they can be found in any brushy or weedy areas, often hopping on the ground. \r\nSome populations on Pacific Coast are permanent residents; those from northern and mountain regions are strongly migratory. Mostly migrates at night. On average, females winter farther south than males. \r\nWhite-crowned sparrows are cavity nesting birds and remain an invasive species, not protected by federal law nor covered under the 1917 Migratory Bird Treaty Act. ','',NULL,'','\r\nhttps://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/09210541/DSCF9355-1.jpg\r\n','','','The white-crowned sparrow (Zonotrichia leucophrys) is very adaptable and lives in a variety of habitats, including:\r\nBreeding: Patchy boreal forests, alpine meadows, coastal scrub, and other grassy areas with scattered shrubs or trees\r\nWintering: Brushy fields, agricultural areas, roadsides, and thickets\r\nOther habitats: Tundra, high alpine meadows, forest edges, coniferous forests, gardens, parks, chaparral, and well-wooded suburbs along Pacific ','The white-crowned sparrow (Zonotrichia leucophrys) has a wide range, including breeding grounds in Alaska and Manitoba, east to Newfoundland and Labrador, and south into the western mountains to central California and northern New Mexico. In the winter, they can be found in southern British Columbia, Idaho, and Nebraska east to the Atlantic, and extending as far south as central Mexico. Some populations on the Pacific Coast are permanent residents, while those from northern and mountain regions are strongly migratory. Females winter farther south than males. \r\n',0),(28,'Mourning Dove','Mourning Dove','columbidae ',19,'brown','grey','black',NULL,NULL,0,'brown','black','grey',0,'black',NULL,'uncommon','uncommon','uncommon','m','Zenaida macroura','mourning_dove.jpg','https://cdn.jonswanservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/26224109/DSCF4612.jpg',0,'female mourning doves are similar in appearance to males, but are generally duller brown and a little smaller.','The mourning dove (Zenaida macroura) is a medium-sized songbird with a delicate bill, small head, and long tail. It is a member of the Columbidae family of doves and pigeons, and is also known as the American mourning dove, the rain dove, the chueybird, and the turtle dove. Mourning doves are common in all seasons and regions, and are generally unbothered by humans','Mourning doves are slaty-brownish above with dark spots on their wings and back, and have a gray upper body with large black spots on the wing coverts and a pale peach-colored lower body. Males are 9.1–13.4 in (23–34 cm) long and weigh 3.4–6.0 oz (96–170 g), while females weigh 3.0–5.5 oz (86–156 g). \r\nMourning doves are named for the mournful sound of their owl-like cooing. They are generally monogamous and form strong pair bonds. In warmer areas, these birds may raise to six broods in a season, and mortality can reach 58% a year for adults and 69% for the young. \r\nYoung mourning doves leave the nest at about 15 days, and stay nearby to be fed for next 1–2 weeks. The crop milk is gradually augmented by seeds, and fledging takes place in about 11–15 days. ','',NULL,'','','','','Mourning doves (Zenaida macroura) are commonly found in many habitats in temperate parts of North America, including:\r\nOpen country: Fields, meadows, grasslands, and pastures\r\nWoodland edges: Scattered trees, forests, and shrublands\r\nUrban and suburban habitats: Towns, roadsides, and backyards\r\nOther habitats: Coasts, deserts, savannas, and thicket','Mourning doves (Zenaida macroura) are common throughout North America, from southern Canada to Panama, and include the Caribbean. They breed from southern Canada south through the lower 48 U.S. states and Mexico to Panama, and also occur in the West Indies. Northern populations tend to be migratory, wintering from the northern U.S. through southern Mexic',0),(29,' Savannah Sparrow',' Savannah Sparrow','sparrows',12,'white','brown','yellow','black',NULL,0,'white','grey','yellow',0,'black','rare','rare','rare','rare','s','Passerculus sandwichensis','savannah_sparrow.jpg',NULL,1,'','The Savannah sparrow (Passerculus sandwichensis) is a medium-sized songbird that is common in North America. They are found in open areas with low-lying vegetation, such as grasslands, fallow fields, and thick grassy areas. \r\n','Savannah sparrows are 4.3–6 inches long, with males being slightly larger. They have brown upper parts with black streaks, white underparts with thin brown streaks on the breast, and a distinct yellow patch on the face in front of the eye. They also have a short, notched tail, a small head, and crown feathers that often flare up to give the bird a small peak. \r\nSavannah sparrows are inconspicuous, with high, thin voices. During breeding season, males sing from perches like fenceposts, shrubs, or trees, a buzzing, insect-like song that is lower-pitched than the preceding, with a low final buzz. \r\nSavannah sparrows are monogamous and will often raise two broods in a season. Both parents bring food to the nestlings, and young leave the nest about 8–11 days after hatching. \r\nSavannah sparrows are medium-distance migrants, with some resident populations along the coast of California and in Mexico. They arrive on spring breeding grounds ranging from late February in Kentucky to early May in Alaska, and depart for their winter range between mid-September and early November. \r\n\r\nThe Savannah sparrow is not endangered federally, but its habitat is threatened. The greatest threat to the Belding\'s Savannah sparrow in California is the destruction of its salt marsh habitat. The Bay Area has seen a 90% decline in tidal marshland since the 1800s. Other threats to the Savannah sparrow include:\r\nPesticides: Can knock down insect prey populations and injure or kill the birds\r\nClimate change: Can affect the Savannah sparrow\r\nUrbanization: Has caused populations to decline\r\nChanges in farming practices: Has caused populations to decline\r\nMowing of hayfields: Can destroy nests and young','',NULL,'','','','','Savannah sparrows (Passerculus sandwichensis) live in grasslands with few trees, including meadows, pastures, grassy roadsides, sedge wetlands, and agricultural fields. They can also inhabit tidal salt-marshes and estuaries along coastlines, and among the shrubby willows of the tundra at the northern extent of their breeding range','\r\nSavannah sparrows are medium-distance migrants that breed in North America, with some populations being resident along the coast of California and in Mexico. They breed in Alaska, Canada, northern, central, and Pacific coastal United States, Mexico, and Guatemala. Pacific and Mexican breeders are resident, but other populations migrate, wintering from the southern United States across Central America and the Caribbean to northern South America',0);
